City Crime Comparison Project
Seattle & Chicago Unified Crime Data Analysis

What This Project Does
This project merges two separate crime datasets — one from Seattle and one from Chicago —
into a single unified table, then runs analyses to compare crime patterns across both cities.

Project Value
Question You Can AnswerHowWhat crime types are most common in each city?Category breakdown chartAre crimes increasing or decreasing over time?Year-over-year line chartWhat time of day are crimes most likely?Hour-of-day bar chartHow often do crimes lead to arrests in Chicago?Arrest rate by categoryAre crime patterns seasonal?Month-of-year analysis (extend yourself!)

Folder Structure
crime_project/
│
├── data/
│   ├── seattle_crime.csv      ← Your Seattle source file (you provide)
│   ├── chicago_crime.csv      ← Your Chicago source file (you provide)
│   └── unified_crime.csv      ← Created by script 01
│
├── output/
│   ├── 01_crime_categories.png
│   ├── 02_crime_over_time.png
│   ├── 03_crime_by_hour.png
│   └── 04_chicago_arrest_rate.png
│
├── 01_etl_pipeline.py         ← Step 1: Merge & clean the data
├── 02_analysis.py             ← Step 2: Run analysis & create charts
└── README.md                  ← This file

How to Run
1. Install requirements
bashpip install pandas matplotlib numpy
2. Place your data files
Put your CSV files in the data/ folder:

data/seattle_crime.csv
data/chicago_crime.csv

3. Run the ETL pipeline first
bashpython 01_etl_pipeline.py
This creates data/unified_crime.csv — the clean, merged dataset.
4. Run the analysis
bashpython 02_analysis.py
Charts will be saved to the output/ folder.

The Unified Schema
After ETL, every crime record from both cities looks like this:
ColumnDescriptionExamplecitySeattle or Chicago"Seattle"case_idOriginal report number"2018-305400"datetimeWhen the crime occurred2018-08-16 15:20:00yearYear extracted from datetime2018monthMonth (1–12)8hourHour of day (0–23)15crime_type_rawOriginal label from source"LARCENY-THEFT"crime_categoryStandardized category"Theft"block_addressStreet block"14XX BLOCK OF 2ND AVE"latitudeGPS latitude47.608longitudeGPS longitude-122.338beatPolice patrol zone"M1"arrest_madeWas an arrest made?True / False / NaNdomesticWas it domestic?True / False / NaN

Note: arrest_made and domestic are only available for Chicago.
Seattle rows will have NaN (empty) for these two columns.


Ideas to Extend This Project

Add a map: Plot crime locations on an interactive map using folium
Add more cities: The same ETL pattern works for any city with open crime data
Add seasonality: Compare summer vs. winter crime rates
Machine learning: Predict crime category from time, location, and beat
Dashboard: Build an interactive dashboard with streamlit